article.description:
Nazr Mohammed scored 24 points, and Shareef
Abdur-Rahim added 20 as the Atlanta Hawks routed the New York Knicks 118-89 Wednesday night.
article.headline: Mohammed leads charge with 24 points
article.story:
ATLANTA (AP) -- Nazr Mohammed thought the Knicks were playing hard in the second half. New York coach Don Chaney didn't agree.
Mohammed

Mohammed scored 24 points, and Shareef Abdur-Rahim added 20 as the Atlanta Hawks routed the Knicks 118-89 Thursday night. "I'm never going to say a professional team lay down," Mohammed said. "I want to give us some credit. We played tough defense." Chaney was despondent over his team's weak effort. "They beat us to loose balls," Chaney said. "They got a lot of easy baskets. They got spot-up jumpers. It's not about being tired. You have to compete and play hard and be aggressive. Come out fighting. We did not fight tonight. We allowed our lack of being able to score affect us defensively." Jason Terry matched his season high with 11 assists for the Hawks, who have won six of seven at home and five of six overall. New York, which had won three of four, dropped to 8-24 on the road. Kurt Thomas led the Knicks with 19 points and 11 rebounds. After Latrell Sprewell hit an 8-foot jumper to cut Atlanta's lead to 62-52 early in the third quarter, the Hawks went on a 29-10 run that ended with Mohammed's reverse layup. New York followed Sprewell's basket by going scoreless on its next six trips, missing five shots and committing a turnover. "It was just an awful game," said Sprewell, who scored 15 points but missed all three of his 3-point attempts. "We can play a lot better than we what we played today. This is not the way we want to finish the season. We just keep going the opposite direction. Guys have to have pride." Mohammed, who scored 12 points on 6-for-8 shooting in the third quarter, had his best offensive game since scoring a career-high 30 in a loss to the Los Angeles Clippers on Nov. 5. "You don't remember those games," said Mohammed, the Hawks' center. "I'd already forgotten about it, to tell you the truth. I'll keep this one with me." Terry hit a 3-pointer over Mark Jackson with 2.6 seconds left in the second quarter to give Atlanta a 62-48 lead, its biggest of the first half. "We just didn't let up," Terry said. "That's what we have to have. Keep after the other team, no matter what the score is. That's what we did." Allan Houston was just 3-for-12 from the field, finishing with 10 points, and the Knicks got a combined 2-for-12 effort from reserve center Othella Harrington and reserve guard Charlie Ward. Chaney was irritated by his team's lack of intensity on defense. "I do know there is a correlation between our inability to hit shots and our defense," Chaney said. "That has to change. Whether we had tired legs, I don't know. But you have to represent yourself on the floor defensively. You cannot let a team -- I don't care how well they're playing -- you can't let a team shoot as well as we let them shoot." Clarence Weatherspoon pulled down a game-high 12 rebounds for the Knicks. Game notes
Abdur-Rahim left Philips Arena with 6:34 left in the third quarter to fly to California to be his wife, DeeDee, for the birth of their first child. ... Harrington fell and twisted his right ankle late in the fourth quarter. X-rays were negative. ... The Hawks, who lost the first three games of the season series, haven't been swept by the Knicks since the 1974-75 season. ... Each team entered with a 26-40 record. ... The Knicks dropped to 0-17 this season on the road when trailing after halftime. ... Knicks guard Howard Eisley, in the second season of a seven-year, $42-million contract did not play for the second time in three games. After going scoreless in 10 minutes of the Knicks' win over Memphis on Tuesday, Eisley questioned Chaney's decision not to play him more.
